title: Mystery FEL droops are being caused by the laser heater feedback wandering around.
text: Both the 06:30 and 07:50 instances of FEL drooping look like they are due to the laser heater feedback moving around. See the plots below - it correlates pretty well with M2H mirror vertical position. In the 8:15 meeting there was a mention of problems with the feedback loop that adjusts the heater camera waveplates to maintain proper image intensity. I think the intensity on the cameras is changing, which causes the laser spot centroid calculation to change, which the laser heater steering feedback then reacts to. The heater gain right now is very high: 2 mJ w/ heater on, 0.3 mJ w/ heater off. So, the beam is apparently very sensitive to small heater disturbances.

title: New Laser Heater Waveplate Feedback:
text: I've added a new and improved laser heater waveplate feedback to the IN20/Laser Laser Heater tab. This feedback aims to keep the CH1 and VHC camera intensities within usable ranges. It's pretty simple but should work well for general running. If you want the feedback to actuate, set the control to LHWP FB ON. If you don't want the feedback to actuate, set the control to LHWP FB OFF. There are buttons to start/stop/restart the feedback process, and there is an indicator which will be red and green depending on if the feedback process is running (green) or not (red). The process needs to be running and the selector set to LHWP FB ON for the feedback to actuate. It should recognize if there isn't beam, the shutter is in etc. and will not try to actuate. For now, the process running indicator is white, as I need to reboot SIOC:SYS0:AL02 to get the new monitor PV live and will do that during the PAMM tomorrow. The feedback process is currently running, and the indicator should work properly tomorrow after the SIOC reboot.
